02:00.870 --> 02:02.370
(sighing):
Oh.

02:02.370 --> 02:04.370
Hey, greet-amundo!

02:04.370 --> 02:05.380
Fonzie,
cover your eyes.

02:05.380 --> 02:06.960
Cover my eyes, all right.

02:06.960 --> 02:08.039
Sit down.

02:08.039 --> 02:10.550
How can I sit down if I
can't see where I'm going?

02:10.550 --> 02:12.550
Come on.
Easy does it.

02:13.050 --> 02:14.050
There you are.
Thanks.

02:14.050 --> 02:15.840
Okay, everybody
can open your eyes.

02:18.090 --> 02:20.590
Well, why did we have
our eyes closed?

02:20.590 --> 02:21.470
Look.

02:22.890 --> 02:25.900
On the counter,
there is a bag of garbage.

02:25.900 --> 02:27.430
How did that
get there?

02:27.430 --> 02:29.020
That's a good trick, Dad.

02:29.520 --> 02:31.020
Oh, yeah, listen, next
time tell me in advance,

02:31.020 --> 02:33.520
I'll bring all my friends over;
we'll laugh hysterically.

02:33.520 --> 02:35.770
All right, will everybody
just calm down please?
All right.

02:35.770 --> 02:38.360
Marion, would you bring
the garbage over here please?

02:38.360 --> 02:40.860
Howard, I'm not
having fun.

02:40.860 --> 02:42.530
Who is?

02:42.530 --> 02:43.610
That's it?

02:43.610 --> 02:45.620
That's-that's what we
all closed our eyes for?

02:45.620 --> 02:47.620
Look, will you just calm down
for a minute please?

02:47.620 --> 02:49.450
Marion, I want you to bring
the garbage over here.

02:49.450 --> 02:50.540
Right over here.

02:52.590 --> 02:54.340
Good!

02:54.340 --> 02:57.930
(laughter)

02:57.930 --> 03:01.430
Dad, I think maybe you better
go upstairs and take a rest.

03:01.430 --> 03:02.430
(laughter)

03:02.430 --> 03:03.930
It's not funny.

03:03.930 --> 03:05.940
Now look at this rug, and
I've got to pick it up.

03:05.940 --> 03:07.940
No, no, no, no, no!
Leave it alone,

03:07.940 --> 03:08.940
That's clean garbage.

03:08.940 --> 03:10.440
I just picked it fresh.

03:10.440 --> 03:11.520
Picked it fresh?

03:11.520 --> 03:13.530
Maybe I better go upstairs
and take a little rest.

03:13.530 --> 03:14.530
(laughs)

03:14.530 --> 03:16.030
I've been breaking
myself up all week.

03:16.030 --> 03:16.950
(laughter)

03:18.620 --> 03:20.700
All right, everybody come
over here and gather around.

03:20.700 --> 03:22.200
I want to show you
some plans.
Oh, come on, Dad.

03:22.200 --> 03:25.210
Come on,
right over here.

03:25.210 --> 03:28.210
Now then, it has always been

03:28.210 --> 03:31.290
my secret ambition
to be an inventor.

03:31.290 --> 03:32.830
You never told me that.

03:32.830 --> 03:33.910
It was a secret.

03:33.910 --> 03:35.500
Oh.

03:35.500 --> 03:36.750
Oh, I'm gonna
clean up that garbage.

03:36.750 --> 03:39.340
Now, just sit down,
Marion, please.

03:39.340 --> 03:42.340
Now, exactly two weeks ago,
the same thing happened to me

03:42.340 --> 03:43.890
that just happened to Mother.

03:43.890 --> 03:45.760
Is this your idea
of revenge?

03:48.060 --> 03:50.560
And I suddenly thought
to myself, I mean,

03:50.560 --> 03:53.070
in this day and age,
here we are in the '50s,

03:53.570 --> 03:56.070
that a person should not
have to carry the garbage out

03:56.070 --> 03:57.570
15 times a week.

03:57.570 --> 03:59.070
Hey, you know,
I totally agree.

03:59.070 --> 04:00.570
That's why I never
have the same chick

04:00.570 --> 04:03.440
pick up garbage, take
it out twice in a row.

04:04.990 --> 04:06.080
Oh, that's good, good.

04:06.080 --> 04:07.080
Thank you,
thank you.

04:07.080 --> 04:09.080
Well, anyway, I thought
that there should be

04:09.080 --> 04:11.580
some way to sort of keep it
in the kitchen, you know?

04:11.580 --> 04:13.590
Sort of push it
all together.

04:13.590 --> 04:15.090
And maybe only take it out
once or twice a week.

04:15.090 --> 04:16.459
You know what I mean?

04:16.459 --> 04:18.040
Sure.

04:18.040 --> 04:19.540
It's called piling
it up in the corner.

04:19.540 --> 04:21.130
(laughs)

04:21.130 --> 04:24.630
No, I mean putting it in
some kind of a special container

04:24.630 --> 04:26.770
and-and squeezing it
all together.

04:26.770 --> 04:28.550
Oh, yuck, Dad!

04:28.550 --> 04:31.140
I can't believe we're having
this conversation.

04:33.140 --> 04:34.140
I can't stand it.

04:34.140 --> 04:35.440
I've got to clean up
that garbage.

04:35.440 --> 04:37.030
Hey, I'll tell you
something, Mrs. C.,

04:37.030 --> 04:39.530
I think the Big H. here's
got the right idea.

04:39.530 --> 04:41.900
I think what you're
talking about, if I get it,

04:41.900 --> 04:43.980
is that you want to
squeeze it all together

04:43.980 --> 04:47.990
like they do with old cars
when they put them to rest.

04:47.990 --> 04:49.490
Exact-amundo!

04:49.490 --> 04:50.490
Whoa!

04:52.960 --> 04:54.960
Hey, hey, Dad, you know,
it's too bad you don't have

04:54.960 --> 04:57.880
some, uh, big corporation
behind this idea, you know?

04:57.880 --> 04:59.470
Why do I need a big corporation?

04:59.470 --> 05:01.970
Listen, all of the great
inventions in life

05:01.970 --> 05:02.970
have been by the little man.

05:02.970 --> 05:04.420
You know the Wright Brothers?

05:04.420 --> 05:06.970
They invented the airplane
in their own bicycle shop.

05:06.970 --> 05:08.470
Yeah, but they were
just trying to build

05:08.470 --> 05:11.890
a very wide bicycle
and it took off.

05:11.890 --> 05:13.480
And Jenny Piccolo,

05:13.480 --> 05:15.570
she invented the first
see-through nightie.

05:15.570 --> 05:17.150
Marion.

05:17.150 --> 05:21.150
I don't wear a
see-through nightie.

05:21.150 --> 05:23.160
Will you talk
to Joanie, please?

05:23.160 --> 05:25.580
Dear, I'm sure
you're wrong.

05:25.580 --> 05:28.160
It was a man named
Frederick in Hollywood.

05:30.500 --> 05:31.580
Well, Fonzie, what do
you think of the plans?

05:31.580 --> 05:33.080
Uh, I'll tell you, see,

05:33.080 --> 05:35.080
I think they're very good
for a start, Mr. C.

05:35.080 --> 05:36.090
What do you mean "for a start"?

05:36.090 --> 05:37.090
I'm all ready to build it.

05:37.590 --> 05:39.090
Oh, well,
you can build this, you know,

05:39.090 --> 05:40.090
but it ain't going
to work.

05:40.090 --> 05:42.130
What? Why
won't it work?

05:42.130 --> 05:43.210
Well, right here,
the spring action

05:43.210 --> 05:44.210
ain't going to make it,
you know?

05:44.210 --> 05:45.680
Well, what else
am I going to use?

05:45.680 --> 05:47.210
Hydraulic lifts.

05:47.210 --> 05:48.300
Really?

05:48.300 --> 05:50.300
Oh, yeah,
the cylinders right in there.

05:50.300 --> 05:52.390
You know, um, uh,
on, on a garage floor,

05:52.390 --> 05:54.390
you got
the hydraulic lift, right?

05:54.390 --> 05:56.860
You press a button,
it kind of raises the car up?

05:56.860 --> 06:01.190
Yeah.
Well, with garbage,
instead of raise, push.

06:01.190 --> 06:04.030
Hey, Dad, I think that's
your solution right there.

06:04.030 --> 06:07.120
Oh, boy, hydraulics-- I
don't know much about that.

06:07.120 --> 06:09.040
I'm not very good
with my hands.

06:09.040 --> 06:10.570
Oh, I wouldn't say that.
Marion.

06:13.710 --> 06:16.790
He's, uh, great at card tricks.

06:20.800 --> 06:23.800
Dad, why don't you just
get, uh, Fonzie to help you?

06:23.800 --> 06:25.300
He's great
with his hands.

06:25.300 --> 06:26.300
He's a mechanical genius.

06:26.300 --> 06:27.300
Heyyy.

06:27.300 --> 06:28.810
(Fonzie and Richie chuckle)

06:28.810 --> 06:29.760
Well, how about
it, Fonzie?

06:30.310 --> 06:31.310
You want to work
on this together?

06:31.310 --> 06:33.310
Look, gentlemen,
I am very busy.

06:33.310 --> 06:35.810
I don't think I
have the time, huh?

06:35.810 --> 06:37.310
Oh, Fonz?
Yeah?

06:37.310 --> 06:41.320
Uh, you know, you, you really
should go in on it with Dad.

06:41.320 --> 06:42.600
Why?

06:42.600 --> 06:45.190
Why, Dad?

06:45.190 --> 06:47.190
Talk.
Oh.

06:47.190 --> 06:49.360
Well, golly,
gee, Fonz.
Oh, for...

06:49.360 --> 06:50.780
I mean,

06:50.780 --> 06:53.360
it's the, uh, the thrill
of... of invention,

06:53.360 --> 06:57.170
the, the excitement of it, and,
uh, and you'd be great at it.

06:57.170 --> 06:58.250
Yeah.
Really...

06:58.250 --> 06:59.590
Really good.
...you could help Howard,

06:59.590 --> 07:01.090
work with him.

07:03.210 --> 07:05.260
How can I turn a
face like that down?

07:06.840 --> 07:07.880
All right, I'll see
what I can do, huh?

07:07.880 --> 07:10.430
All right, Fonz!

07:10.430 --> 07:11.930
You know
you got my steam up?

07:11.930 --> 07:13.930
Come on, let's go
out to the garage.

07:13.930 --> 07:16.690
I want to show you
all the parts I got so far.

07:16.690 --> 07:19.860
Come on, partner.

07:19.860 --> 07:22.440
♪ ♪

07:29.150 --> 07:30.730
One question.

07:30.730 --> 07:32.790
Who said "Stop the music?"

07:32.790 --> 07:34.650
POTSIE & RALPH:
Him.

07:35.960 --> 07:38.790
There are people
trying to dance here.

07:38.790 --> 07:40.880
Oh, well, Fonz, you see,

07:40.880 --> 07:42.880
this isn't really
a formal dance.

07:42.880 --> 07:44.880
This is just a rehearsal
for us, and, uh,

07:44.880 --> 07:47.170
